	8.	Calvão, F. (2019). Crypto-miners: Digital labor and the power of blockchain technology. Economic Anthropology, 6(1), 123-134 ￼ ￼. (Ethnographic study on cryptocurrency mining as a form of digital labor; discusses how the work of mining secures blockchain transactions and enables formation of digital communities, framing mining as “productive, meaningful action” in social context ￼.)
	9.	Budkowski, M. (2025). Escaping the Memeplex. (Online essay, Feb 6, 2025) ￼. (Analyzes how ecosystems like Bitcoin and Ethereum are shaped by their memeplexes. Notably observes that Bitcoin’s memeplex – centered on “digital gold” and an anti-establishment ethos – creates a cohesive but sometimes rigid tribe ￼.)
	10.	CoinMooner. (2025). How Dogecoin Turned Memes Into a $70 Billion Market Trend. (Blog article, Feb 26, 2025) ￼. (Describes the rise of meme-based cryptocurrencies; notes that coins like Dogecoin and Shiba Inu leveraged humor and internet meme culture to shape financial markets, proving the power of digital culture in economic domains ￼.)

⸻

PhD Program Curriculum: Digital Culture Evolution and Memetic Biochemistry

To train researchers and practitioners in the theory and application of memetic biochemistry and digital cultural evolution, we propose a structured PhD program. This interdisciplinary program combines cultural theory, digital sociology, cryptography, and data science, equipping graduates to analyze and influence the evolution of digital communities. Below is an outline of the curriculum, including core courses, research methodologies, seminars, dissertation tracks, and career preparation. Each component is designed with credit hours, learning outcomes, and assessment criteria to ensure a rigorous and comprehensive educational experience.

Program Overview

Degree: Ph.D. in Digital Culture Evolution (Specialization in Memetic Biochemistry)
Duration: 4 years (full-time)
Credit Requirement: 60 credits of coursework + comprehensive exams + dissertation research
Program Objective: Develop expertise in understanding how digital cultures form, evolve, and can be guided, by integrating memetic theory, biochemical analogy, and computational social science. Graduates will be prepared for academic or industry roles requiring deep insight into cultural dynamics in digital ecosystems.

1. Core Courses (Year 1-2) – 18 credits

Each core course is 3 credits, typically involving weekly lectures/seminars, readings, and projects. These establish foundational knowledge in relevant domains:
	•	DCU 701: Introduction to Memetic Theory (3 credits)
Content: History and fundamentals of memetics; Dawkins’ “selfish gene” and meme concept ￼; memeplexes; key thinkers (Blackmore, Shifman); case studies of meme propagation.
Learning Outcomes: Students will be able to explain how memes function as units of cultural evolution and critique memetic theory’s strengths and limitations.
Assessment: Class discussions (20%), a mid-term essay analyzing an internet meme trend with theoretical context (30%), and a final exam (50%).
	•	DCU 702: Digital Cultural Evolution (3 credits)
Content: Principles of cultural evolution in the digital age ￼ ￼; the role of social media, high-fidelity transmission online, and virality; models of cultural diffusion and innovation; introduction to network science for culture (e.g., how information spreads on Twitter).
Learning Outcomes: Students will interpret digital cultural phenomena using evolution paradigms and apply models (e.g., diffusion of innovations, epidemic models for memes).
Assessment: Problem sets on modeling meme spread (30%), presentation on a digital culture case study (20%), final paper proposing an evolutionary model for a chosen digital trend (50%).
	•	DCU 703: Cryptographic Foundations in Digital Communities (3 credits)
Content: Overview of cryptography and blockchain fundamentals relevant to socio-technical systems; Bitcoin protocol and its cryptographic “genetics” ￼; smart contracts; how technical design influences community behavior (e.g., consensus algorithms and governance).
Learning Outcomes: Students will grasp how cryptographic rules shape the “DNA” of blockchain communities and be able to analyze a protocol’s features in social terms.
Assessment: Technical report dissecting a cryptocurrency’s protocol and community (40%), in-class quizzes (20%), final exam (40%).
	•	DCU 704: Behavioral Economics and Praxis Analysis (3 credits)
Content: Fundamentals of behavioral economics and game theory in online contexts; incentive structures for user participation (e.g., token economics, reputation systems); identifying praxis units and their payoffs; rational vs. irrational behaviors (herding, fear of missing out).
Learning Outcomes: Students will analyze how incentives and psychological factors drive the praxis units (actions) in digital platforms and propose improvements to align individual incentives with community health.
Assessment: Case study analysis of an online platform’s incentive system (30%), simulation project modeling user behavior under different rules (20%), final exam (50%).
	•	DCU 705: Cultural Data Science (3 credits)
Content: Data analysis techniques for cultural data – text mining (for semantic primes evolution), network analysis (for meme propagation networks), sentiment analysis (for attitude layer measurement), and introduction to machine learning for pattern detection in community data.
Learning Outcomes: Students will gain practical skills in extracting and quantifying cultural signals from digital traces (e.g., Twitter data, forum posts) and linking them to theoretical constructs like memes or attitudes.
Assessment: Lab assignments using Python/R to analyze a dataset (50%), final project where students choose a digital community and map its memetic/behavioral landscape through data (50%).
	•	DCU 706: Ethics and Governance of Digital Communities (3 credits)
Content: Ethical considerations in studying and intervening in online cultures (privacy, consent, algorithmic bias); governance models of digital communities (decentralized vs centralized moderation, DAO governance); the impact of policy and design on cultural evolution (e.g., how content moderation shapes meme spread).
Learning Outcomes: Students will articulate ethical best practices and critique governance decisions from a cultural evolution perspective, preparing them to responsibly apply their expertise.
Assessment: Participation in debate on a case (e.g., Facebook’s algorithm changes) (20%), policy brief writing assignment proposing governance improvements for an online community (30%), final take-home exam (50%).

2. Research Methodologies (Year 2) – 9 credits

Methodology courses focus on specific techniques for conducting original research on digital cultural evolution:
	•	DCU 721: Quantifying Memetic Stability (3 credits)
Focus: Methods to measure and track memes and their stability: longitudinal content analysis, memetics statistics (frequency, mutation rate, survival rate of memes ￼), survey design for memetic resonance. Introduces tools like Google Trends, web scraping, and visualization of meme trajectories.
Outcome: Students will design a study to quantify the stability or change of a particular meme or set of memes over time and interpret the results in context.
Assessment: Students conduct a mini-research project analyzing one meme’s trend over at least 1 year, produce a report with metrics and visualization (70%), plus peer review of classmates’ projects (30%).
	•	DCU 722: Measuring Praxis Unit Effectiveness (3 credits)
Focus: Mixed-method approaches to evaluate behaviors in communities: statistical analysis of user contribution distributions (e.g., Gini coefficient of contributions), A/B testing of interventions to boost desirable actions, participant observation and diaries to qualitatively assess what motivates key contributors. Techniques include social network analysis to see which actions correlate with network growth or resilience.
Outcome: Students will be able to identify key praxis units in a community and apply methods to gauge their impact (e.g., does mentoring new users increase retention?).
Assessment: Methodological proposal paper where each student picks a community (open-source project, subreddit, etc.) and outlines how to determine which user actions most impact that community’s success, including proposed metrics and any pilot data (100%).
	•	DCU 723: Mapping Semantic Prime Evolution (3 credits)
Focus: Linguistic and semantic analysis methods: Natural Language Processing (NLP) for topic modeling, keyword extraction, and semantic network mapping over time. Also, qualitative analysis of core documents or archives to detect shifts in fundamental concepts. Students will practice with tools to construct semantic networks (nodes as concepts, edges as co-occurrence links) for a corpus of community text (like forum data) at different timestamps.
Outcome: Students gain experience in detecting and interpreting changes in a community’s discourse at a fundamental level (e.g., introduction of new jargon or fading of old terminology).
Assessment: Project where students map the semantic network of a community at two different periods (e.g., year 2015 vs 2025) and write an analysis of how the core lexicon has evolved and what that implies for the community’s knowledge layer (100%).

3. Seminars & Colloquia (Year 1-3) – 4 credits

To stay abreast of current developments and encourage scholarly discourse, the program includes seminars and colloquia:
	•	DCU 730: Interdisciplinary Seminar in Memetics and Digital Culture (1 credit per semester, 4 semesters = 4 credits)
Format: Weekly or biweekly seminar featuring guest lectures, student presentations, and roundtable discussions. Guests will include experts in memetics (e.g., authors of recent memetics research), cryptography and blockchain (developers or researchers), digital sociology (scholars studying online movements), and media studies (meme creators or curators). For example, a cryptography expert might talk about the philosophy behind a decentralized social network’s design, or a memeticist might present on internet meme warfare.
Learning Outcomes: Students will engage with cutting-edge ideas and network with professionals. They will learn to discuss their research in a multidisciplinary setting and gain feedback.
Assessment: These seminars are graded Pass/Fail based on attendance (minimum 80% of talks), submission of brief reflection essays on a certain number of talks (e.g., 1-page reflection on any 5 talks of their choice, linking it to their own research interests), and at least one presentation by the student (such as a research progress update or literature review) during the program.

4. Dissertation Tracks (Year 3-4)

Toward the end of coursework, students choose a dissertation track that aligns with their interest. Each track represents a broad area of inquiry within memetic biochemistry and digital culture:
	•	Track A: Empirical Analysis of Memetic Transmission in Digital Networks
Description: Emphasizes quantitative and data-driven research on how memes spread and evolve. A student in this track might, for instance, analyze millions of tweets to model competition and selection among political memes ￼ ￼, or examine Reddit communities to see how insider language predicts community longevity.
Possible Dissertation Topics: “Competition and Selection Among Internet Memes during Election Cycles,” “Memetic Diffusion Patterns in Encrypted Messaging Apps,” “Role of Influencers in Shaping Memeplexes on TikTok.”
	•	Track B: Case Studies of Blockchain Communities
Description: Focuses on in-depth studies of specific blockchain or decentralized communities (e.g., Ethereum, Dogecoin, Decentralized Autonomous Organizations) using the memetic biochemistry framework. Combines qualitative community observation with analysis of on-chain data and forums.
Possible Topics: “The Memetic Immune System of Ethereum: How Competing Visions Affect Protocol Governance,” “Dogecoin as a Cultural Phenomenon: Humorous Memes and Economic Behavior ￼,” “Comparative Memetic Biochemistry of DAO vs. Traditional Open-Source Project.”
	•	Track C: Predictive Models for Memetic Adoption and Cultural Change
Description: Oriented around building and testing models (using simulations or AI) that predict how cultural changes occur. This could involve agent-based modeling of users with certain meme “genotypes” interacting, or machine learning models predicting community health from early indicators.
Possible Topics: “Agent-Based Simulation of Praxis Unit Spread in a Gamified Learning Community,” “Early Warning System for Toxic Meme Emergence in Online Forums,” “Predicting Community Schisms by Tracking Semantic Drift.”

For each track, students work closely with faculty advisors to refine their research question and methodology. In Year 3, students will complete a comprehensive exam (covering core theory and methods), then defend a dissertation proposal. Year 3 and 4 are primarily devoted to conducting research, publishing preliminary results (encouraged), and writing the dissertation.

Dissertation Assessment: The PhD culminates in a written dissertation and an oral defense. Assessment criteria include originality of research, methodological rigor, contribution to knowledge (e.g., extending memetic theory, revealing new insights into digital culture), and the ability to articulate how findings could apply in real-world contexts (such as platform design or policy).

5. Career Applications and Professional Development (ongoing, non-credit)

Throughout the program, students receive training and opportunities preparing them for diverse careers:
	•	Academic Career Preparation: Workshops on writing and publishing journal articles, presenting at conferences, and teaching pedagogy (many will serve as teaching assistants for undergraduate classes in related subjects). Students will be encouraged to submit portions of their research to conferences (e.g., AAAI or Web Science for computational work, or media studies conferences for qualitative work) and to network with scholars through the seminar series.
	•	Industry and Policy Engagement: Given the applicability of this field to technology companies, social media firms, and policy think-tanks, the program will facilitate internships or consulting projects in relevant organizations. For example, a student might intern at a social media company’s integrity team, applying memetic analysis to content moderation strategy, or at a blockchain startup focusing on community governance. Career panels will be organized with representatives from blockchain industry (on community management and crypto-economics), cybersecurity (on information warfare and memes), and media analytics firms.
	•	AI-Driven Cultural Analysis: As AI tools become prevalent, students will also be exposed to how artificial intelligence can both analyze and participate in cultural evolution. This prepares them for roles in tech companies building AI moderation tools or culture-focused AI systems.
	•	Credit-bearing Practicum (optional): An optional 1-2 credit practicum can be taken in year 3 where a student works on a real-world project (such as advising an NGO on combating misinformation spread, or helping an online community improve retention) and produces a report reflecting on the experience with theoretical insight. This is evaluated pass/fail but noted on the transcript to show practical experience.

Learning Outcomes: By the end of the program, graduates will have:
	•	A deep theoretical understanding of how digital cultures form and evolve, grounded in memetic biochemistry analogy and related models.
	•	Advanced skills in both qualitative and quantitative research methodologies to study online communities and cultural data.
	•	Experience in applying theory to real cases, whether through case studies, simulations, or internships, bridging the gap between academia and practical solutions.
	•	A portfolio of scholarly work (publications or prototypes) demonstrating their expertise, and a clear path to career opportunities in academia (e.g., postdoctoral research or faculty positions in media studies, information science, etc.), industry (e.g., research scientist in social media or gaming companies, data analyst for digital marketing, cultural strategist), or policy (e.g., advising governments or NGOs on digital engagement and information campaigns).

Assessment & Graduation: To successfully graduate, students must:
	•	Complete all coursework with a satisfactory GPA (e.g., >3.3/4.0).
	•	Pass the comprehensive examination (written and oral components covering key literature and methods).
	•	Successfully propose, conduct, and defend an original dissertation research project.
	•	Demonstrate at least one practical outreach (like a conference presentation or published paper) before defense.
	•	Fulfill any teaching or service requirements set by the department (such as mentoring junior students or assisting in organizing the seminar series).

This PhD program thus produces well-rounded experts ready to tackle the complexities of digital cultural evolution. Graduates will be capable of analyzing phenomena like viral social movements, online extremist meme networks, or the community dynamics of decentralized technologies, with a unique perspective that combines humanistic insight and scientific method. The training in memetic biochemistry not only enriches academic understanding but also provides a powerful lens for industry and policy to navigate the cultural challenges of the digital era.


<br>

Introduction to Least Action in Cultural and Technological Evolution

The principle of least action in physics states that the trajectory or behavior of a system between two states is the one which extremizes (usually minimizes) the action – a quantity defined as the time-integral of the Lagrangian (kinetic minus potential energy). In classical mechanics, this yields the same equations of motion as Newton’s laws, but framed as a variational problem. Max Planck once called least action “the most general principle of physics” ￼, highlighting its broad applicability from optics to quantum mechanics. Modern reformulations even link it to thermodynamics: maximizing entropy production under constraints is equivalent to minimizing action ￼ ￼. In other words, nature not only increases entropy (per the Second Law) but does so along paths of least resistance (least time or least action) given the constraints.

This physics principle can be a powerful metaphor for cultural and technological evolution. Just as physical systems seek configurations that minimize free energy or action, societies and technologies often evolve along paths of “least effort” or minimal resistance. Cultural evolution can be viewed as a thermodynamic process: culture is a society’s means to consume free energy ￼. According to the thermodynamic account, social changes are natural processes that aim to diminish energy differences within the system in the least possible time ￼. In practice, this means societies develop highly efficient (minimal-action) ways to organize and transmit energy and information – manifesting as norms, institutions, and technologies ￼. For example, Ilya Prigogine’s work on dissipative structures showed that when energy flows through a system, it can self-organize into ordered patterns (like convection cells or tornadoes) that dissipate energy more efficiently ￼. Figure 1 illustrates Rayleigh–Bénard convection cells forming in a heated fluid – a spontaneous structure that emerges to expedite heat dissipation (in effect, a least-action solution for moving heat). Life itself can be seen as an even more effective dissipative structure: it arose by removing constraints and generating diverse “dissipators” (organisms, ecosystems) to accelerate entropy production ￼. In short, whether we look at physics, biology, or culture, we find a common theme: systems evolve along pathways that minimize “action” (or free energy) while respecting the constraints of their environment.

￼ Figure 1: Rayleigh–Bénard convection cells forming in a fluid layer heated from below. Such dissipative structures arise naturally to move heat upward and entropy outward more efficiently, exemplifying a self-organized path of least action for energy dissipation.

Now consider Bitcoin’s emergence through this lens. Bitcoin can be viewed as a new memetic organism in the cultural/technological landscape – one that had to navigate multiple constraints (economic, computational, social) and find a viable path to existence. We can hypothesize that Bitcoin followed a “path of least action” constrained by the problems it needed to solve (digital trust, double-spending, decentralization) and the resistances it faced (regulatory crackdowns, user adoption hurdles, computing costs). Indeed, Bitcoin’s design appears to be minimal yet sufficient: it combined just the right components (peer-to-peer networking, cryptographic proof-of-work, economic incentives) to solve the digital currency problem with no central authority. Earlier digital currency attempts (e.g. DigiCash, e-gold) failed largely due to reliance on centralized intermediaries that became points of failure. Satoshi Nakamoto explicitly noted this, saying that prior e-currency projects were “doomed” by their centrally controlled nature, and Bitcoin was “the first time we’re trying a decentralized, non-trust-based system” ￼. In other words, Bitcoin’s breakthrough was to remove the biggest constraint (the need for a trusted third party) by using a decentralized protocol – arguably the path of least resistance in the long run, since it sidestepped government regulations and single points of attack that brought down its predecessors.

In parallel, consider the KAP model (Knowledge–Attitude–Practice) in social change as an entropic force in cultural evolution. KAP is a framework often used to drive behavior change: individuals first acquire new knowledge, which shapes their attitudes, eventually leading to adoption of new practices ￼. In a stagnant cultural system where there is underspeciation (too little diversity of ideas and practices), KAP interventions inject new information and attitudes – increasing entropy in the memetic “gene pool.” This added diversity can jostle the system out of local optima or gridlock. One can think of a culture stuck in tradition as a ball trapped in a local energy minimum; an influx of fresh knowledge or perspectives through education (KAP) is like adding heat to the system, allowing the ball to roll over the hill into a potentially lower (better) basin. In the sections that follow, we will develop these analogies rigorously: mapping Bitcoin’s trajectory onto a least-action framework, and exploring how KAP-driven entropy injection helps bypass cultural gridlock. We will also outline a thermodynamic view of memetic evolution – treating cultural adaptations as Hamiltonian trajectories in an energy landscape – and discuss how these principles might guide future engineering of digital communities and decentralized systems.

Bitcoin as a Path of Least Action

Bitcoin’s evolution can be mapped as a minimization problem constrained by economics, computation, and governance. In its inception, Bitcoin had to solve a very hard optimization: achieve secure, distributed consensus (to prevent double-spending) with minimal trust and without a central coordinator. This is akin to finding a low-action path in a rugged landscape of possibilities. Satoshi’s solution was remarkably elegant. By using proof-of-work (a costly computation) to timestamp and secure transactions, and rewarding miners with bitcoin, the system aligned economic incentives with network security. This approach connected the abstract digital ledger to the physical world of energy, effectively making it costly to deviate from the honest path. The result was a self-enforcing equilibrium: as long as the majority of miners are rational and follow incentives, the blockchain grows along the honest chain (the path of least “cost”). One might say Bitcoin’s consensus follows an “action principle”: the honest chain is the one that has expended the most cumulative proof-of-work (i.e. the most action), and the network always prefers the heaviest (least action-deviating) chain. Importantly, this happened without any central planning – it’s an emergent property of many actors each minimizing their own cost and maximizing reward.

The Bitcoin network also features an automatic regulator that keeps it on an even keel: the difficulty adjustment. Every two weeks, the protocol adjusts the mining difficulty to target a 10-minute block interval, counteracting changes in total hash power. This feedback mechanism ensures that the system quickly settles into a steady state despite fluctuations in miner participation. In effect, it finds a moving optimum: if blocks come in too fast (hash power above equilibrium), difficulty increases, slowing down production; if too slow, difficulty decreases. This way, new coins are mined at a predetermined rate regardless of how many miners join ￼. The difficulty adjustment exemplifies Bitcoin’s tendency toward a minimal-action trajectory – it prevents runaway dynamics (like exponential block production or complete stall) and keeps the network at a stable throughput. Economically, it means miners operate around the breakeven point where marginal cost equals marginal reward, an equilibrium analogous to a ball resting at the bottom of a potential well.

Another way to see Bitcoin’s history as a least-action path is to examine how it navigated technical and social forks. Changes to the protocol are often resisted if they entail too much “action” – whether that action is technical risk, implementation complexity, or social upheaval. Successful upgrades tend to be those that improve efficiency or security without dramatically increasing system complexity (i.e., they lower the action). For example, the 2017 Segregated Witness (SegWit) upgrade provided a way to increase throughput and fix transaction malleability without increasing the block size limit via a contentious hard fork. SegWit separated signature data from transactions, reducing the effective size of each transaction and thereby allowing more transactions per block ￼. This made transactions lighter and fees lower, a clear reduction in the “energy” per transaction, and it was deployed as a soft fork (backwards-compatible change) to minimize disruption. The network, after much debate, gravitated toward SegWit – essentially choosing the path that solved the immediate problem (congestion) with the least upheaval. Another example is the recent Taproot upgrade (2021). Taproot introduced more powerful smart contract capabilities and signature aggregation, yet it actually streamlined transaction verification and improved privacy. By batching multiple signatures into one (Schnorr aggregation), Taproot makes complex multi-signature transactions more efficient in terms of cost and size ￼ ￼. These upgrades (SegWit, Taproot) can be seen as lowering the action threshold for the network: they each optimized Bitcoin’s functionality relative to the status quo, and thus were eventually accepted by the network which “prefers” lower-action states when all else is equal.

It’s instructive to contrast this with instances where the community did not reach consensus, such as the block size debate. In that dispute, one camp argued for a simple increase of the block size (to 2MB or 8MB) to improve throughput, while another camp warned that such a change would increase resource requirements for nodes and threaten decentralization ￼ ￼. The impasse led to a schism: Bitcoin Cash hard-forked away with a larger block size, whereas Bitcoin Core activated SegWit and kept blocks small. We can interpret this as a bifurcation between two local minima in the socio-technical landscape: one prioritizing immediate throughput (lower on-chain fees) at the cost of higher node resource “action,” and the other prioritizing decentralization (many small nodes) at the cost of off-chain solutions for scaling. The main Bitcoin network arguably followed the globally lower-action trajectory in the long run, because it maintained the low barrier to running a node (preserving decentralization and security) while enabling layer-2 solutions like the Lightning Network to handle high-volume transactions off-chain. In least-action terms, Bitcoin’s evolution favored minimizing social and systemic action (avoiding centralization, avoiding frequent hard forks) even if that meant some trade-offs in the short term. Over time, the system’s adaptability – adding features like SegWit, Lightning, Taproot – has allowed it to continue growing without abandoning its original equilibrium. Each adaptation addresses a constraint (whether block capacity, fungibility, or script flexibility) in a way that minimally disturbs the existing order, thereby following an incremental gradient-descent-like evolution toward a more robust and efficient cryptocurrency.

In summary, Bitcoin’s emergence and growth can be viewed as a least action path through a space of constraints. Its design aligned incentives so that every actor (miners, nodes, users) pursuing their own minimal action (cost) contributes to the global optimum (a secure, stable ledger). Innovations that lower the “action” (energy, cost, or complexity) per transaction tend to be adopted, whereas changes that would raise the overall action or create imbalance face resistance. This perspective provides a unifying way to understand why Bitcoin took the shape it did – and perhaps to predict what kinds of changes are likely to succeed in its future evolution (those that preserve or reduce the aggregate action needed to maintain consensus).

KAP as an Entropic Maximization System

While systems naturally tend toward least-action configurations, this can lead to stagnation if the system gets stuck in a suboptimal local minimum. In biological evolution, lack of variation can cause a population to settle in a fitness valley and stop evolving; similarly, in cultural evolution, underspeciation – too little differentiation of ideas or practices – can create a kind of evolutionary gridlock. Everyone thinks and acts the same way, so new solutions or adaptations don’t emerge. This is where entropy injection becomes crucial. By introducing randomness or diversity into the system, we can provide the “kick” needed to escape local minima and explore new possibilities. The Knowledge–Attitude–Practice (KAP) model serves as a mechanism for such entropy injection in social systems. It breaks the process of behavior change into three steps: first gaining new knowledge, then forming new attitudes/beliefs, and finally adopting new practices/behaviors ￼. Each step increases the informational entropy of the culture – new knowledge adds new memes to the pool, changing attitudes upsets the prior consensus, and new practices create variation in behaviors.

￼ Figure 2: A schematic “energy landscape” with a shallow local minimum (left dip) and a deeper global minimum (right dip). A system can get trapped in the local minimum (a suboptimal stable state). Escaping it requires an injection of energy or entropy to overcome the barrier (hill) between the local and global minima. In cultural terms, this means introducing new ideas or practices (via KAP or other innovations) to break out of stagnation and reach a more optimal state.

The effect of KAP on a stagnant culture is analogous to simulated annealing in optimization. In simulated annealing, a small amount of random “heat” is added to a system to allow it to jump out of local minima in search of a global minimum (see Figure 2). Likewise, a community stuck with outdated practices may need a burst of new ideas (through education, exposure, or crisis) to shake up entrenched attitudes. Knowledge diversification is essentially raising the entropy of the memetic mix – introducing variety so that selection has something to act upon. Once enough diversity is present (many new approaches or viewpoints tried), the system can undergo selection and retention of the fittest ideas, potentially settling into a much more adaptive equilibrium (the global minimum). Underspeciation (cultural gridlock) is thus overcome by entropic maximization: deliberately broadening the range of knowledge and behaviors to allow evolution to proceed again.

One can frame cultural action as an integral over time in analogy to physical action. In physics, the action $S = \int L dt$ accumulates the Lagrangian over a time path. Similarly, cultural or social action can be thought of as accumulating changes (knowledge, attitudes, practices) over history. A stagnant culture has very little new “action” being accumulated – it’s as if the Lagrangian (the drive for change minus resistance) is nearly zero, so the integral over time yields no significant evolution. KAP serves to increase the Lagrangian by injecting a disparity – new knowledge creates a tension between current attitudes and possible practices, essentially increasing the “potential energy” of the status quo and prompting movement. As that cultural action integrates over time, the society follows a new trajectory, ideally toward a state of lower internal stress (e.g., better alignment with the environment or human needs). We can even speak of a Hamiltonian in memetic space: imagine coordinates representing various cultural traits and momenta representing the impetus of trends or movements. Adaptation then is the trajectory these coordinates follow under forces (like economic pressure, technological change, or ideological influence) that can be derived from a sort of memetic potential. While this is metaphorical, it suggests that we could, in principle, describe cultural dynamics with equations of motion, where knowledge acts as kinetic energy, entrenched traditions as potential wells, and KAP-like interventions as perturbations that add energy to the system.

Crucially, adding entropy (diversity) alone isn’t enough – it must be coupled with a selection mechanism to actually yield progress. This is where attitude and practice in KAP come in: not only are new ideas introduced, but attitudes are formed to favor some of those ideas, and then practices implement them, which is effectively selection and retention. In evolutionary terms, variation is introduced, then selection (through attitudes and social norms) chooses which variations to amplify, and practice cements those into habit (retention/heredity). This variation–selection–retention cycle is the core of cultural evolution ￼ ￼. The KAP model ensures that the cycle keeps turning even when a culture has been static, by continuously feeding new variation (knowledge) and translating it into lived experience (practice). Without such entropic input, a culture could remain indefinitely in a suboptimal steady state – a phenomenon we see in isolated societies that resist outside influence, often at the cost of adaptability.

It’s insightful to note that human culture itself may have evolved as nature’s way of avoiding local optima that individual, biological evolution alone could not escape. Cognitive scientist and AI researcher Yoshua Bengio proposed that culture and language allow humans to overcome complex learning challenges that a single brain cannot solve in one lifetime ￼ ￼. For example, high-level abstract knowledge is hard to acquire from scratch (a single brain might get stuck in a learning local minimum), but via cultural transmission (language, teaching, science) we effectively do a form of parallel, social search in the space of ideas and share the results. Bengio’s hypothesis implies that the evolution of ideas (memetics) is a faster search algorithm atop the slower genetic evolution, helping us find better solutions (global minima in fitness or understanding) than we could via individual trial-and-error ￼. In our context, KAP is a microcosm of that: it’s an engine for social learning and adaptation. By increasing the entropy of the system (through new knowledge) and then shaping that entropy into ordered change (new practices), KAP drives the cultural system toward a new configuration that ideally has lower free energy – meaning the society functions with less internal conflict or inefficiency than before. In short, KAP maximizes entropy transiently to enable a larger reduction of free energy eventually, analogous to how a heated metal can be reshaped into a lower-energy structure once it cools.

Thermodynamics of Cultural Evolution and Praxis Units

To formalize these intuitions, we can draw from thermodynamics and information theory. Cultural evolution can be seen as a process of energy flow and entropy management within a population of minds and institutions. Each idea or practice has an energetic cost and benefit (in terms of resources, effort, satisfaction, etc.), and cultures tend to settle into configurations that locally optimize these (hence traditions that “work” tend to stick around). However, as environments change, those once-optimal configurations might become suboptimal. The thermodynamic driver is always present: a culture consumes free energy (natural resources, human effort) and aims to dissipate it in fulfilling ways (meeting needs, solving problems) ￼ ￼. If the culture is effective, it will use praxis – practical action informed by knowledge – to continually adjust and improve that energy transduction. We can think of praxis units as quanta of cultural action: each unit could be an adoption of a new tool, a social reform, or even a single executed idea. These are like the “moves” a culture makes in the phase space of possibilities. Over time, the integral of many praxis units forms the trajectory of that culture’s evolution (much as an integral of instantaneous Lagrangian yields the action along a physical trajectory).

In thermodynamic terms, cultural evolution often behaves like a gradient descent on a fitness landscape, but the landscape itself can shift. One useful concept is the idea of a free energy landscape in culture – analogous to those used in protein folding or neural networks. Here, free energy could correspond to a combination of social stress, unfulfilled needs, and unused resources (basically, potential for improvement). A low free-energy state would be one where the society is stable, needs are met, and resources are efficiently utilized (high entropy production). Cultures tend to move toward such states, reducing internal free energy by solving problems and standardizing effective memes (this is like minimizing surprise or uncertainty, as in Karl Friston’s Free Energy Principle for adaptive systems). However, this “descent” can get stuck on entropy-minimizing or rather entropy-reducing plateaus – states where the culture is orderly but not optimal (low entropy but also low innovation). To continue downward (toward better states), sometimes entropy must first increase (system becomes more disordered or diverse) so it can then find a lower valley beyond the current hill. This is analogous to how heating up a solid can allow it to re-crystallize into a more stable form upon cooling.

Communities in the blockchain and digital culture space provide vivid examples of phase transitions under entropic pressure. A phase transition in this context is a sudden, qualitative change in the state of a network or community – for instance, a fork, a mass adoption event, or a collapse of consensus. Consider the split of Ethereum into Ethereum Classic and the main Ethereum chain after The DAO hack in 2016. The community faced a crisis (a large-scale theft due to a smart contract bug) and was divided on whether to change the ledger’s history to undo the damage. This was a high-energy, high-entropy moment for Ethereum’s culture: intense debate (entropy in attitudes) and exploration of options (multiple proposed outcomes). The eventual hard fork was essentially a bifurcation or phase change – one group of participants opted to alter the state (creating a new phase of the network with slightly different rules), while another group refused and maintained the original chain. We can view the pre-fork state as a supercooled liquid on the verge of crystallization: the DAO hack injected entropy (disorder), and the system couldn’t maintain its prior “phase” of consensus, resulting in a split into two more internally coherent phases (ETH and ETC). Similarly, the Bitcoin vs. Bitcoin Cash split can be seen as a phase transition triggered by accumulated stress (the block size debate introduced divergent attitudes and goals – increasing memetic entropy – until the network could no longer stay in a single coherent phase and split into two ordered phases each with more uniform ideology).

Another kind of phase transition is adoption booms, like the sudden surge of interest in NFTs or meme stocks. These can be viewed through the lens of critical mass and network effects – once a threshold is passed, the behavior of the system changes discontinuously (e.g., an avalanche of new users joining). Entropic forces often underlie these transitions: for example, a highly homogeneous skeptical attitude toward crypto might keep adoption low (everyone agrees it’s risky or useless). But as knowledge spreads and a few attitude shifts occur (perhaps due to influencers or visible success stories), entropy in opinions increases; beyond a critical point, a cascade happens where the predominant attitude flips from skepticism to FOMO (fear of missing out). The system’s macro state (public sentiment) has then switched phase. In physics, we’d model such phenomena with something like an Ising model (spins flipping) or percolation theory – indeed, researchers have applied statistical physics models to social consensus and found entropy measures that signal the tipping point between consensus and plurality ￼. High information entropy in opinion distribution corresponds to a mixed state (no consensus), whereas low entropy corresponds to a strong consensus (ordered state). At the critical point, small perturbations (a bit more entropy from new information) can tip the balance and create a new large-scale order (a new consensus or the fragmentation into camps).

Throughout these changes, praxis – the enactment of ideas – is what actually moves the system. One can think of praxis as the integration of knowledge into the real world. Each praxis event (like deploying a code upgrade, or starting a new governance process, or an individual deciding to use Bitcoin for the first time) has an “action” associated with it. Some actions will be more energetically costly or risky, and those will only happen if enough potential (free energy) has built up to justify them. For instance, switching a blockchain’s consensus algorithm (as Ethereum’s long-planned move from Proof-of-Work to Proof-of-Stake) is a high-action move – it took years of building pressure (concerns about energy use, economic modeling, technical R&D) to reach the point where the transition (“The Merge”) was executed. That transition can be seen as a thermodynamic phase change in Ethereum’s operation: a significant drop in energy consumption (over 99%) at the cost of fundamentally altering the system’s security mechanism. The cultural attitudes had to be carefully prepared (most of the community aligned in favor) – in other words, entropy had to be managed so that by the time of the change there was little dissent (low entropy consensus to actually execute the phase shift). It’s a fascinating dance: entropy rises during the exploratory phase (research, debate, trial testnets) and entropy falls when the new order is crystallized (the new consensus algorithm becomes the norm).

From a bird’s-eye thermodynamic view, memetic evolution works like this: drive the system with entropy-increasing forces when it’s stuck (to explore new configurations), then let selection decrease entropy by favoring a particular order that better dissipates energy (solves problems). The gradient descent analogy holds during the selection/convergence periods (culture refining an innovation, spreading a best practice), whereas a metastable jump or uphill move is allowed during the variation periods (culture experimenting wildly, many failures discarded). Over long timescales, this results in punctuated equilibria – long stable periods (least-action plateaus) interrupted by bursts of rapid change (entropy-driven reconfigurations). Each stable state can be thought of as a locally minimized action configuration given the prevailing constraints, and each burst is the system renegotiating constraints to reach a new configuration.

Implications and Applications

Understanding cultural and technological evolution in terms of least action and entropy has practical implications. If we can recognize the signs of a system nearing a local minimum (stagnation) or approaching a phase transition, we might better predict or guide the next steps. For instance, in blockchain governance, this perspective suggests that proposals which reduce the overall “action” required for the network to operate will have an intrinsic advantage. “Action” here could mean energy expenditure, complexity of coordination, or even opportunity cost for participants. A governance change that simplifies processes or automates trust (thereby lowering the energy and attention people must spend to maintain the system) is likely to be favored by the community over one that adds complexity or cost. This could be used to forecast which improvement proposals are more likely to pass. One could even formulate a rudimentary Lagrangian for a blockchain’s state – balancing terms for security, decentralization, and performance – and attempt to identify the path of least action for upgrades. Such a model might have predicted, for example, that Bitcoin would favor soft forks like SegWit over a contentious hard fork, because the latter, while technically straightforward, carried enormous “social action” costs (splitting the community).

Engineering digital cultural evolution could involve deliberately tuning entropy. In decentralized autonomous organizations (DAOs) or online communities, one often encounters gridlock when a dominant narrative or rule-set becomes hard to change (analogous to underspeciation). Using the KAP model, community leaders could inject entropy by seeding new ideas (e.g., bringing in external experts, running experiments or pilot projects) to broaden the solution space. Then, by measuring feedback (attitudes, outcomes of the pilots) they can guide the community toward adopting the successful innovations (thus returning to a lower-action state on a new footing). Essentially, this is simulated annealing for social consensus: periodically introduce a bit of “noise” (diverse perspectives, provocative questions) to avoid premature lock-in of suboptimal norms. Algorithmic governance systems (like futarchy or quadratic voting mechanisms) might incorporate this by design, for instance by allowing random small policy experiments or diversity in decision-making panels to ensure a continual flow of variation.

Another application is in the domain of AI and memetic content. As AI systems (like recommendation algorithms or large language models) play a bigger role in shaping culture, we want to avoid converging to monoculture or echo chambers – that’s cultural underspeciation which can lead to fragility and groupthink. An action-entropy framework would advise that we periodically introduce novel content and viewpoints (entropy) into recommendation systems to keep the cultural landscape robust. This mirrors the exploration-exploitation tradeoff in reinforcement learning: purely exploiting (showing people only what they already like) minimizes immediate “effort” but can lead to a local minimum of engagement; some exploration (showing something different) might decrease short-term reward but open up new, potentially richer seams of content. Designing AI that follows least action principles in the long run might mean it seeks to minimize user discontent and maximize information diversity over time, which could yield more stable engagement and healthier discourse.

We can also speculate about mathematical models for least-action cultural adaptation. One promising line of work is to adapt the variational principles used in physics directly to evolutionary dynamics. For example, the Free Energy Principle (FEP) in neuroscience casts perception and learning as a process of minimizing “surprisal” or free energy – essentially aligning internal models with the external world. This has been extended to describe cultural ensembles as well ￼, suggesting that communities might collectively minimize surprise (or unmet expectations). In a cultural FEP model, a community has a model of the world that it updates with shared narratives and paradigms; it will resist information that causes too much surprise (cognitive dissonance) unless enough entropy (randomness) enters to force a paradigm shift, at which point it can settle into a new model that better accounts for the data (thus lowering free energy again). Another approach could be to use Hamiltonian Monte Carlo in idea space – imagine sampling different policy combinations as states in a Hamiltonian system where momentum corresponds to how entrenched an idea is, and the potential corresponds to how well the idea satisfies needs vs. conflicts with constraints. Such a system would “walk” the idea landscape, guided by a least action principle, toward high-likelihood (low free-energy) cultural configurations. Although these models are in their infancy, early attempts like Annila and Salthe’s work on natural networks as thermodynamic systems indicate that many features of real networks (including social ones) “follow from least-time free energy consumption” ￼.

In practice, leaders and innovators can apply these principles by asking: What is the biggest source of friction (action) in our system, and can we eliminate it? Bitcoin eliminated the central intermediary (friction in trust); the internet eliminated distance as friction for communication; perhaps the next cultural revolution will eliminate some cognitive friction (maybe through brain-computer interfaces or universal education). Conversely, one should ask: Is our community stagnating due to lack of new ideas? If yes, it’s time to inject entropy – encourage divergent thinking sessions, invite outsiders, or run safe-to-fail experiments. By toggling between entropy-increasing and action-minimizing modes, we can steer complex systems much like a thermostat cycles between heating and cooling to maintain a comfortable temperature.

Conclusion

We have explored how the principle of least action – a bedrock concept of physics – provides a rich theoretical framework for understanding memetic biochemistry and digital evolution. In physics, least action encapsulates how natural systems elegantly balance forces and constraints to find optimal paths. Analogously, Bitcoin’s emergence was not a random accident but followed a path of least resistance through the constraints of finance and computing: it found a sweet spot where economic incentives and cryptography created a self-sustaining system with minimal required trust. Its continued evolution through upgrades and forks shows a tendency to prefer solutions that reduce cost, energy, or complexity (minimized action) while satisfying the necessary constraints of security and decentralization.

On the other hand, purely minimizing action can lead to dead-ends (local minima). That’s where entropy and diversity – the realm of “memetic mutations” – come into play. The KAP model illustrates how injecting knowledge and shaking up attitudes can increase entropy enough to dislodge cultural systems from gridlock. We likened this to raising the temperature so that a new configuration – potentially a more globally optimal one – can be found. In the language of memetic thermodynamics, cultures need a judicious mix of order and disorder: periods of stable optimization and bursts of exploratory innovation. Praxis is the link converting one to the other – it is applied knowledge, the integrated action that actually realizes lower-energy states (solutions) out of the chaos of possibilities. Each community or network can be thought of as traversing a Hamiltonian landscape, with its own generalized coordinates (values, technologies) and momenta (social momentum, institutional inertia), perpetually seeking an equilibrium that maximizes its purpose (entropy dissipation, problem solving) with minimal wasted effort.

By applying these analogies, we gain not just poetic insight but potentially predictive power. We can anticipate that systems under strain will either adapt via a least-action adjustment or fracture via a phase transition; we can plan interventions that either reduce the “action” needed for cooperation (making change easier) or increase the entropy when innovation is stalled (making change possible). Future research could formalize these ideas: imagine quantifying the “action” of a social movement, or the entropy of a public debate, and writing evolution equations for them. Such models might help in crafting better protocols for blockchain governance, in designing resilient AI-mediated ecosystems, or even in guiding societal transformations (for example, to a sustainable economy) by identifying where the current system is stuck in a local minimum and what kind of entropy injection could trigger a transition to a better state.

In closing, the convergence of least action and memetics offers a compelling vision of digital and cultural evolution as self-organizing, energy-driven processes. It suggests that much as chemical reactions or planetary orbits can be derived from a variational principle, so too might the arc of technology adoption or the lifecycle of online communities. The concepts of energy, entropy, and action form a common language bridging physics, biology, and sociology. By leveraging that language, we can better understand phenomena like Bitcoin not just as isolated historical events, but as expressions of deeper natural laws playing out in the information realm. And by doing so, we equip ourselves with principles that can guide the engineering of future cultural shifts – helping us inject the right amount of entropy, find the paths of least action, and steer our collective evolution toward robust and flourishing equilibria.

